<section id="nutrition-tips">

	<div class="wrap">

		<header>

			<h2>Top Nutrition Tips</h2>

		</header>

		<div class="container">

			<ol>

				<li>

					<h3>Eat breakfast.</h3>

					<p>Choose a breakfast with lean protein, whole grains, and fruits/vegetables. A good option is oatmeal with almonds and berries or a toaster waffle with yogurt and fruit.</p>

				</li>

				<li>

					<h3>Make 1/2 your plate fruits and vegetables.</h3>

					<p>Fruits and vegetables provide vitamins, minerals, and fiber. Stock up on frozen so they are always available.</p>

				</li>

				<li>

					<h3>Watch portion sizes.</h3>

					<p>Get out measuring cups to check how accurate your portions are to the serving sizes.  Use smaller plates and bowls to control portions.</p>

				</li>

				<li>

					<h3>Be active.</h3>

					<p>Being active controls stress and weight. Aim to be physically active everyday.</p>

				</li>

				<li>

					<h3>Fix healthy snacks.</h3>

					<p>It can be easy to prepare healthy snacks to have available when hungry. Carry around a piece of fruit with some nuts.</p>

				</li>

				<li>

					<h3>Get to know food labels.</h3>

					<p>Become familiar with different food label terms. Look at serving sizes and the number of servings. It is important to look for low amounts of trans and saturated fat as well as low sodium.</p>

				</li>

				<li>

					<h3>Get cooking.</h3>

					<p>Cooking meals at home is healthy and cost effective.</p>

				</li>

				<li>

					<h3>Dine out well.</h3>

					<p>Choose foods carefully. Look for terms such as grilled, baked, broiled or steamed.</p>

				</li>

				<li>

					<h3>Drink more water.</h3>

					<p>Water regulates body temperature and transports nutrients and oxygen to cells. Water also carries away waste. Aim to have 9-13 cups per day.</p>

				</li>

			</ol>

		</div>

	</div>

</section>